# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: data-loss-prevention
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] An **Internet filter** is a type of Internet censorship that restricts or controls the content an Internet user is capable to access, especially when utilized to restrict material delivered over the Internet via the Web, Email, or other means.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] The motive is often to prevent access to content which the computer's owner(s) or other authorities may consider objectionable.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] When imposed without the consent of the user, content control can be characterised as a form of internet censorship.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Some filter software includes time control functions that empowers parents to set the amount of time that child may spend accessing the Internet or playing games or other computer activities.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] The term "content control" is used on occasion by CNN, *Playboy* magazine, the *San Francisco Chronicle*, and *The New York Times*.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] However, several other terms, including "content filtering software", "web content filter", "filtering proxy servers", "secure web gateways", "censorware", "content security and control", "web filtering software", "content-censoring software", and "content-blocking software", are often used.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] "Nannyware" has also been used in both product marketing and by the media.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Industry research company Gartner uses **"secure web gateway"** (SWG) to describe the market segment.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Some products log all sites that a user accesses and rates them based on content type for reporting to an "accountability partner" of the person's choosing, and the term accountability software is used.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Internet filters, parental control software, and/or accountability software may also be combined into one product.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Those critical of such software, however, use the term "censorware" freely: consider the Censorware Project, for example.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Filters can be implemented in many different ways: by software on a personal computer, via network infrastructure such as proxy servers, DNS servers, or firewalls that provide Internet access.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] No solution provides complete coverage, so most companies deploy a mix of technologies to achieve the proper content control in line with their policies.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] E-mail filters act on information contained in the mail body, in the mail headers such as sender and subject, and e-mail attachments to classify, accept, or reject messages.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] , a type of statistical filter, are commonly used.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Both client and server based filters are available.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] This type of filter is installed as software on each computer where filtering is required.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] This filter can typically be managed, disabled or uninstalled by anyone who has administrator-level privileges on the system.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Content-limited (or filtered) ISPs are Internet service providers that offer access to only a set portion of Internet content on an opt-in or a mandatory basis.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Anyone who subscribes to this type of service is subject to restrictions.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] functionality to filter outbound as well as inbound information.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] All users are subject to the access policy defined by the institution.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] The filtering can be customized, so a school district's high school library can have a different filtering profile than the district's junior high school library.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] This type of filtering is implemented at the DNS layer and attempts to prevent lookups for domains that do not fit within a set of policies (either parental control or company rules).
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] offer filtering options as part of their services.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] can be also be used for this purpose, though client-side only.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] offer users the option of turning on a safety filter.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] When this safety filter is activated, it filters out the inappropriate links from all of the search results.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] If users know the actual URL of a website that features explicit or adult content, they have the ability to access that content without using a search engine.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Some providers offer child-oriented versions of their engines that permit only child friendly websites.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Some offer security software which includes parental controls.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] operating system also includes content-control software.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] The Internet does not intrinsically provide content blocking, and therefore there is much content on the Internet that is considered unsuitable for children, given that much content is given certifications as suitable for adults only, e.g.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Internet service providers (ISPs) that block material containing pornography, or controversial religious, political, or news-related content en route are often utilized by parents who do not permit their children to access content not conforming to their personal beliefs.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Content filtering software can, however, also be used to block malware and other content that is or contains hostile, intrusive, or annoying material including adware, spam, computer viruses, worms, trojan horses, and spyware.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Most content control software is marketed to organizations or parents.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] It is, however, also marketed on occasion to facilitate self-censorship, for example by people struggling with addictions to online pornography, gambling, chat rooms, etc.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Self-censorship software may also be utilised by some in order to avoid viewing content they consider immoral, inappropriate, or simply distracting.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] A number of accountability software products are marketed as *self-censorship* or *accountability software*.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] These are often promoted by religious media and at religious gatherings.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Content filtering technology exists in two major forms: application gateway or packet inspection.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] For HTTP access the application gateway is called a web-proxy or just a proxy.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Such web-proxies can inspect both the initial request and the returned web page using arbitrarily complex rules and will not return any part of the page to the requester until a decision is made.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] In addition they can make substitutions in whole or for any part of the returned result.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Packet inspection filters do not initially interfere with the connection to the server but inspect the data in the connection as it goes past, at some point the filter may decide that the connection is to be filtered and it will then disconnect it by injecting a TCP-Reset or similar faked packet.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] The two techniques can be used together with the packet filter monitoring a link until it sees an HTTP connection starting to an IP address that has content that needs filtering.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] The packet filter then redirects the connection to the web-proxy which can perform detailed filtering on the website without having to pass through all unfiltered connections.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] This combination is quite popular because it can significantly reduce the cost of the system.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] There are constraints to IP level packet-filtering, as it may result in rendering all web content associated with a particular IP address inaccessible.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] This may result in the unintentional blocking of legitimate sites that share the same IP address or domain.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] For instance, university websites commonly employ multiple domains under one IP address.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Moreover, IP level packet-filtering can be surpassed by using a distinct IP address for certain content while still being linked to the same domain or server.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Gateway-based content control software may be more difficult to bypass than desktop software as the user does not have physical access to the filtering device.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] However, many of the techniques in the Bypassing filters section still work.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Content labeling may be considered another form of content-control software.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] In 1994, the Internet Content Rating Association (ICRA) — now part of the Family Online Safety Institute — developed a content rating system for online content providers.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Using an online questionnaire a webmaster describes the nature of their web content.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] A small file is generated that contains a condensed, computer readable digest of this description that can then be used by content filtering software to block or allow that site.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] ICRA labels come in a variety of formats.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] These include the World Wide Web Consortium's Resource Description Framework (RDF) as well as Platform for Internet Content Selection (PICS) labels used by Microsoft's Internet Explorer Content Advisor.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] ICRA labels are an example of self-labeling.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Similarly, in 2006 the Association of Sites Advocating Child Protection (ASACP) initiated the Restricted to Adults self-labeling initiative.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] ASACP members were concerned that various forms of legislation being proposed in the United States were going to have the effect of forcing adult companies to label their content.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] The RTA label, unlike ICRA labels, does not require a webmaster to fill out a questionnaire or sign up to use.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Both labels are recognized by a wide variety of content-control software.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] The Voluntary Content Rating (VCR) system was devised by Solid Oak Software for their CYBERsitter filtering software, as an alternative to the PICS system, which some critics deemed too complex.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] It employs HTML metadata tags embedded within web page documents to specify the type of content contained in the document.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Only two levels are specified, *mature* and *adult*, making the specification extremely simple.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] The Australian Internet Safety Advisory Body has information about "practical advice on Internet safety, parental control and filters for the protection of children, students and families" that also includes public libraries.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] NetAlert, the software made available free of charge by the Australian government, was allegedly cracked by a 16-year-old student, Tom Wood, less than a week after its release in August 2007.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Wood supposedly bypassed the $84 million filter in about half an hour to highlight problems with the government's approach to Internet content filtering.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] The Australian Government has introduced legislation that requires ISPs to "restrict access to age restricted content (commercial MA15+ content and R18+ content) either hosted in Australia or provided from Australia" that was due to commence from 20 January 2008, known as Cleanfeed.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Cleanfeed is a proposed mandatory ISP level content filtration system.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] It was proposed by the Beazley led Australian Labor Party opposition in a 2006 press release, with the intention of protecting children who were vulnerable due to claimed parental computer illiteracy.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] It was announced on 31 December 2007 as a policy to be implemented by the Rudd ALP government, and initial tests in Tasmania have produced a 2008 report.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Cleanfeed is funded in the current budget, and is moving towards an Expression of Interest for live testing with ISPs in 2008.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Public opposition and criticism have emerged, led by the EFA and gaining irregular mainstream media attention, with a majority of Australians reportedly "strongly against" its implementation.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Criticisms include its expense, inaccuracy (it will be impossible to ensure only illegal sites are blocked) and the fact that it will be compulsory, which can be seen as an intrusion on free speech rights.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Another major criticism point has been that although the filter is claimed to stop certain materials, the underground rings dealing in such materials will not be affected.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] The filter might also provide a false sense of security for parents, who might supervise children less while using the Internet, achieving the exact opposite effect.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Cleanfeed is a responsibility of Senator Conroy's portfolio.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] In Denmark it is stated policy that it will "prevent inappropriate Internet sites from being accessed from children's libraries across Denmark".
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] "'It is important that every library in the country has the opportunity to protect children against pornographic material when they are using library computers.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Many libraries in the UK such as the British Library and local authority public libraries apply filters to Internet access.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] According to research conducted by the Radical Librarians Collective, at least 98% of public libraries apply filters; including categories such as "LGBT interest", "abortion" and "questionable".
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] The use of Internet filters or content-control software varies widely in public libraries in the United States, since Internet use policies are established by the local library board.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Many libraries adopted Internet filters after Congress conditioned the receipt of universal service discounts on the use of Internet filters through the Children's Internet Protection Act (CIPA).
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Other libraries do not install content control software, believing that acceptable use policies and educational efforts address the issue of children accessing age-inappropriate content while preserving adult users' right to freely access information.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Some libraries use Internet filters on computers used by children only.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Many legal scholars believe that a number of legal cases, in particular *Reno v.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] American Civil Liberties Union*, established that the use of content-control software in libraries is a violation of the First Amendment.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] The Children's Internet Protection Act [CIPA] and the June 2003 case *United States v.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] The plurality decision left open a future "as-applied" Constitutional challenge, however.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] In November 2006, a lawsuit was filed against the North Central Regional Library District (NCRL) in Washington State for its policy of refusing to disable restrictions upon requests of adult patrons, but CIPA was not challenged in that matter.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] The Court said: "It appears to us that NCRL's filtering policy is reasonable and accords with its mission and these policies and is viewpoint neutral.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] It appears that no article I, section 5 content-based violation exists in this case.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] NCRL's essential mission is to promote reading and lifelong learning.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] As NCRL maintains, it is reasonable to impose restrictions on Internet access in order to maintain an environment that is conducive to study and contemplative thought." The case returned to federal court.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] In March 2007, Virginia passed a law similar to CIPA that requires public libraries receiving state funds to use content-control software.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Like CIPA, the law requires libraries to disable filters for an adult library user when requested to do so by the user.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Utilizing a filter that is overly zealous at filtering content, or mislabels content not intended to be censored can result in over-blocking, or over-censoring.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Overblocking can filter out material that should be acceptable under the filtering policy in effect, for example health related information may unintentionally be filtered along with porn-related material because of the Scunthorpe problem.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Filter administrators may prefer to err on the side of caution by accepting over blocking to prevent any risk of access to sites that they determine to be undesirable.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Content-control software was mentioned as blocking access to Beaver College before its name change to Arcadia University.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Another example was the filtering of Horniman Museum.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] As well, over-blocking may encourage users to bypass the filter entirely.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Whenever new information is uploaded to the Internet, filters can under block, or under-censor, content if the parties responsible for maintaining the filters do not update them quickly and accurately, and a blacklisting rather than a whitelisting filtering policy is in place.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Many would not be satisfied with government filtering viewpoints on moral or political issues, agreeing that this could become support for propaganda.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Many would also find it unacceptable that an ISP, whether by law or by the ISP's own choice, should deploy such software without allowing the users to disable the filtering for their own connections.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] In the United States, the First Amendment to the United States Constitution has been cited in calls to criminalise forced internet censorship.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Many types of content-control software have been shown to block sites based on the religious and political leanings of the company owners.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Examples include blocking several religious sites (including the Web site of the Vatican), many political sites, and homosexuality-related sites.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] *X-Stop* was shown to block sites such as the Quaker web site, the National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law, The Heritage Foundation, and parts of The Ethical Spectacle.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] CYBERsitter blocks out sites like National Organization for Women.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Nancy Willard, an academic researcher and attorney, pointed out that many U.S. public schools and libraries use the same filtering software that many Christian organizations use.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] In 1998, a United States federal district court in Virginia ruled (Loudoun v.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Board of Trustees of the Loudoun County Library) that the imposition of mandatory filtering in a public library violates the First Amendment.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] In 1996 the US Congress passed the Communications Decency Act, banning indecency on the Internet.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Civil liberties groups challenged the law under the First Amendment, and in 1997 the Supreme Court ruled in their favor.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Part of the civil liberties argument, especially from groups like the Electronic Frontier Foundation, was that parents who wanted to block sites could use their own content-filtering software, making government involvement unnecessary.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] In the late 1990s, groups such as the Censorware Project began reverse-engineering the content-control software and decrypting the blacklists to determine what kind of sites the software blocked.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] This led to legal action alleging violation of the "Cyber Patrol" license agreement.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] They discovered that such tools routinely blocked unobjectionable sites while also failing to block intended targets.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Some content-control software companies responded by claiming that their filtering criteria were backed by intensive manual checking.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] The companies' opponents argued, on the other hand, that performing the necessary checking would require resources greater than the companies possessed and that therefore their claims were not valid.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] The Motion Picture Association successfully obtained a UK ruling enforcing ISPs to use content-control software to prevent copyright infringement by their subscribers.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Content filtering in general can "be bypassed entirely by tech-savvy individuals." Blocking content on a device "[will not]…guarantee that users won't eventually be able to find a way around the filter." Content providers may change URLs or IP addresses to circumvent filtering.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Individuals with technical expertise may use a different method by employing multiple domains or URLs that direct to a shared IP address where restricted content is present.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] This strategy doesn't circumvent IP packet filtering, however can evade DNS poisoning and web proxies.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Additionally, perpetrators may use mirrored websites that avoid filters.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Some software may be bypassed successfully by using alternative protocols such as FTP or telnet or HTTPS, conducting searches in a different language, using a proxy server or a circumventor such as Psiphon.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Also cached web pages returned by Google or other searches could bypass some controls as well.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Web syndication services may provide alternate paths for content.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Some of the more poorly designed programs can be shut down by killing their processes: for example, in Microsoft Windows through the Windows Task Manager, or in Mac OS X using Force Quit or Activity Monitor.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Numerous workarounds and counters to workarounds from content-control software creators exist.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Google services are often blocked by filters, but these may most often be bypassed by using *https://* in place of *http://* since content filtering software is not able to interpret content under secure connections (in this case SSL).
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] An encrypted VPN can be used as means of bypassing content control software, especially if the content control software is installed on an Internet gateway or firewall.
[src:data-loss-prevention/content-control-software] Other ways to bypass a content control filter include translation sites and establishing a remote connection with an uncensored device.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-classification-data-management] Data classification can be viewed as a multitude of labels that are used to define the type of data, especially on confidentiality and integrity issues.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-classification-data-management] Classification techniques might be used for reports generated by ERP systems or where the data includes specific personal information that is identified.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-classification-data-management] Many organizations also employ context-based classification that considers factors such as data source, user identity, and application context.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-classification-data-management] Data classification schemes are mandated or implied by numerous regulatory frameworks that require organizations to identify, categorize, and protect sensitive information according to its level of sensitivity.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-classification-data-management] NIST Special Publication 800-60 provides guidelines for mapping information types to security categories, establishing a structured methodology for federal agencies to classify data and apply appropriate security controls based on the potential impact of a security breach.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-exfiltration] In some data exfiltration scenarios, a large amount of aggregated data may be exfiltrated.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-exfiltration] However, in these and other scenarios, it is likely that certain types of data may be targeted.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-exfiltration] Several techniques have been used by malicious actors to carry out data exfiltration.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-exfiltration] The technique chosen depends on a number of factors.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-exfiltration] If the attacker has or can easily gain physical or privileged remote access to the server containing the data they wish to exfiltrate, their chances of success are much better than otherwise.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-exfiltration] For example, it would be relatively easy for a system administrator to plant, and in turn, execute malware that transmits data to an external command and control server without getting caught.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-exfiltration] Similarly, if one can gain physical administrative access, they can potentially steal the server holding the target data, or more realistically, transfer data from the server to a DVD or USB flash drive.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-exfiltration] In many cases, malicious actors cannot gain physical access to the physical systems holding target data.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-exfiltration] In these situations, they may compromise user accounts on remote access applications using manufacturer default or weak passwords.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-exfiltration] In 2009, after analyzing 200 data exfiltration attacks that took place in 24 countries, SpiderLabs discovered a ninety percent success rate in compromising user accounts on remote access applications without requiring brute-force attacks.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-exfiltration] Once a malicious actor gains this level of access, they may transfer target data elsewhere.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-exfiltration] Additionally, there are more sophisticated forms of data exfiltration.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-exfiltration] Various techniques can be used to conceal detection by network defenses.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-exfiltration] For example, Cross Site Scripting (XSS) can be used to exploit vulnerabilities in web applications to provide a malicious actor with sensitive data.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-exfiltration] A timing channel can also be used to send data a few packets at a time at specified intervals in a way that is even more difficult for network defenses to detect and prevent.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-exfiltration] A number of things can be done to help defend a network against data exfiltration.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-exfiltration] One example of detective measures is to implement intrusion detection and prevention systems and regularly monitor network services to ensure that only known acceptable services are running at any given time.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-exfiltration] If suspicious network services are running, investigate and take the appropriate measures immediately.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-exfiltration] Preventive measures include the implementation and maintenance of access controls, deception techniques, and encryption of data in process, in transit, and at rest.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-exfiltration] Investigative measures include various forensics actions and counter intelligence operations.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-loss-prevention-software] Data loss incidents (unauthorized disclosure or deletion of sensitive data) may turn into data leak incidents (data breaches) when media containing sensitive information are lost and then acquired by an unauthorized party, including via data theft.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-loss-prevention-software] However, a data leak is possible without losing the data on the originating side.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-loss-prevention-software] There are limitations to the effectiveness of DLP systems in reducing risk of data loss.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-loss-prevention-software] Technological means for prevention data loss include standard security measures, advanced/intelligent security measures, access control and encryption, and content-aware DLP systems, although only the latter category is typically referred to as DLP.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-loss-prevention-software] Most DLP systems rely on predefined rules to identify and categorize sensitive information.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-loss-prevention-software] Standard security measures, such as firewalls, intrusion detection systems (IDSs), and antivirus software, are widely used to guard against both outsider and insider attacks.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-loss-prevention-software] Intrusion detection systems identify unauthorized use, misuse, and abuse of computer systems by monitoring for behavior patterns that differ from legitimate users.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-loss-prevention-software] Advanced security measures employ machine learning, behavioral analytics, honeypots, temporal reasoning, and activity-based verification to detect abnormal or unauthorized data access patterns.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-loss-prevention-software] Machine learning algorithms enable systems to automatically improve through experience, identifying patterns in large datasets to enhance detection capabilities.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-loss-prevention-software] Content-aware DLP systems detect and prevent unauthorized attempts to copy, transmit, or publish sensitive data.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-loss-prevention-software] These systems use mechanisms such as exact data matching, structured data fingerprinting, statistical methods, rule-based detection, and contextual analysis.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-loss-prevention-software] Network (data in motion) systems operate at egress points and analyze traffic for sensitive information being transmitted in violation of policy.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-loss-prevention-software] Next-generation firewalls and intrusion detection systems often support DLP-like capabilities.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-loss-prevention-software] Endpoint (data in use) systems monitor user actions on desktops, servers, and devices, enabling controls such as blocking copying, printing, screen capture, or unauthorized email transmission.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-loss-prevention-software] Cloud DLP monitors data within cloud services and applies controls to enforce access and usage policies.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-loss-prevention-software] Cloud computing provides on-demand network access to shared computing resources, enabling scalable and flexible data protection strategies.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-loss-prevention-software] These systems help maintain compatibility with existing on-premises DLP infrastructure while addressing issues that are unique to cloud environments such as shared responsibility models, multi-cloud data governance, and shadow IT discovery.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-loss-prevention-software] Data identification techniques classify information as structured or unstructured.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-loss-prevention-software] Roughly 80% of enterprise data is unstructured.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-loss-prevention-software] Recent industry guidance describes data classification and policy alignment as foundational elements of effective DLP programs.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-loss-prevention-software] Vendors also emphasize the role of integrated DLP, analytics, and automation in modern data protection strategies.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-loss-prevention-software] Data distributors may intentionally or unintentionally share data with third parties, after which it is later found in unauthorized locations.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-loss-prevention-software] DLP investigations attempt to determine the source.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-loss-prevention-software] DLP techniques include access controls, encryption, and data retention policies.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-loss-prevention-software] Data encryption transforms readable information into an unreadable format to protect confidentiality, ensuring only authorized parties with the proper decryption key can access the original data.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-loss-prevention-software] "Data in use" refers to data currently being accessed.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-loss-prevention-software] DLP systems may monitor and flag unauthorized manipulation or transfer of such data.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-loss-prevention-software] "Data in motion" refers to data traveling across internal or external networks.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-loss-prevention-software] DLP systems monitor and control this flow.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-loss-prevention-software] False positive management remains a significant issue.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-loss-prevention-software] Policies that are too broad tend to generate alerts that require manual review which may overwhelm security teams and reduce the overall effectiveness of DLP software.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-loss-prevention-software] Privacy and compliance concerns can arise when an organization monitors employees.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-loss-prevention-software] Achieving data security in such situations requires a delicate balance between adequate monitoring and taking care that individual privacy rights are not infringed upon.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-loss-prevention-software] Evasion techniques exist including steganography, encryption, or manipulation of a file's format that can sometimes circumvent DLP detection methods and require continuous updating of detection software.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-loss-prevention-software] The complexity of DLP policy increases substantially in global organizations due to their greater size and operation in disparate jurisdictions.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-loss-prevention-software] DLP software in these cases must often contend with more diverse regulatory requirements, a broader range of data types, and relatively complex business processes.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-loss-prevention-software] This makes it challenging to achieve consistent enforcement across regions and departments.
[src:data-loss-prevention/data-loss-prevention-software] Relevant information privacy laws include the EU General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), HIPAA in the United States, and the California Consumer Privacy Act.
[src:data-loss-prevention/egress-filtering] In computer networking, **egress filtering** is the practice of monitoring and potentially restricting the flow of information outbound from one network to another.
[src:data-loss-prevention/egress-filtering] Typically, it is information from a private TCP/IP computer network to the Internet that is controlled.
[src:data-loss-prevention/egress-filtering] TCP/IP packets that are being sent out of the internal network are examined via a router, firewall, or similar edge device.
[src:data-loss-prevention/egress-filtering] Packets that do not meet security policies are not allowed to leave – they are denied "egress".
[src:data-loss-prevention/egress-filtering] Egress filtering helps ensure that unauthorized or malicious traffic never leaves the internal network.
[src:data-loss-prevention/egress-filtering] In a corporate network, typical recommendations are that all traffic except that emerging from a select set of servers would be denied egress.
[src:data-loss-prevention/egress-filtering] Restrictions can further be made such that only select protocols such as HTTP, email, and DNS are allowed.
[src:data-loss-prevention/egress-filtering] User workstations would then need to be configured either manually or via proxy auto-config to use one of the allowed servers as a proxy.
[src:data-loss-prevention/egress-filtering] Corporate networks also typically have a limited number of internal address blocks in use.
[src:data-loss-prevention/egress-filtering] Egress filtering may require policy changes and administrative work whenever a new application requires external network access.
[src:data-loss-prevention/egress-filtering] For this reason, egress filtering is an uncommon feature on consumer and very small business networks.
[src:data-loss-prevention/egress-filtering] PCI DSS requires outbound filtering to be in place on any server in the cardholder's environment.
[src:data-loss-prevention/egress-filtering] This is described in PCI-DSS v3.0, requirement 1.3.3.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] This refers to information that is already a matter of public record or knowledge.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] With regard to government and private organizations, access to or release of such information may be requested by any member of the public, and there are often formal processes laid out for how to do so.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] The accessibility of government-held public records is an important part of government transparency, accountability to its citizens, and the values of democracy.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] Public records may furthermore refer to information about identifiable individuals that is not considered confidential, including but not limited to: census records, criminal records, sex offender registry files, and voter registration.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] This includes business information that is not subjected to special protection and may be routinely shared with anyone inside or outside of the business.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] However, there are situations in which the release of personal information could have a negative effect on its owner.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] For example, a person trying to avoid a stalker will be inclined to further restrict access to such personal information.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] Furthermore, a person's SSN or SIN, credit card numbers, and other financial information may be considered private if their disclosure might lead to crimes such as identity theft or fraud.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] Some types of private information, including records of a person's health care, education, and employment may be protected by privacy laws.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] Unauthorized disclosure of private information can make the perpetrator liable for civil remedies and may in some cases be subject to criminal penalties.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] Even though they are often used interchangeably, personal information is sometimes distinguished from private information, or personally identifiable information.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] The latter is distinct from the former in that Private information can be used to identify a unique individual.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] Personal information, on the other hand, is information belonging to the private life of an individual that cannot be used to uniquely identify that individual.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] This can range from an individual's favourite colour, to the details of their domestic life.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] The latter is a common example of personal information that is also regarded as sensitive, where the individual sharing these details with a trusted listener would prefer for it not to be shared with anyone else, and the sharing of which may result in unwanted consequences.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] Confidential business information (CBI) refers to information whose disclosure may harm the business.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] Such information may include trade secrets, sales and marketing plans, new product plans, notes associated with patentable inventions, customer and supplier information, financial data, and more.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] Under TSCA, CBI is defined as proprietary information, considered confidential to the submitter, the release of which would cause substantial business injury to the owner.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] The US EPA may as of 2016, review and determine if a company´s claim is valid.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] Classified information generally refers to information that is subject to special security classification regulations imposed by many national governments, the disclosure of which may cause harm to national interests and security.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] The protocol of restriction imposed upon such information is categorized into a hierarchy of classification levels in almost every national government worldwide, with the most restricted levels containing information that may cause the greatest danger to national security if leaked.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] Authorized access is granted to individuals on a need to know basis who have also passed the appropriate level of security clearance.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] Classified information can be reclassified to a different level or declassified (made available to the public) depending on changes of situation or new intelligence.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] Classified information may also be further denoted with the method of communication or access.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] For example, Protectively Marked "Secret" Eyes Only or Protectively Marked "Secret" Encrypted transfer only.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] Indicating that the document must be physically read by the recipient and cannot be openly discussed for example over a telephone conversation or that the communication can be sent only using encrypted means.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] Often mistakenly listed as meaning for the eyes of the intended recipient only the anomaly becomes apparent when the additional tag "Not within windowed area" is also used.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] Data privacy concerns exist in various aspects of daily life wherever personal data is stored and collected, such as on the internet, in medical records, financial records, and expression of political opinions.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] In over 80 countries in the world, personally identifiable information is protected by information privacy laws, which outline limits to the collection and use of personally identifiable information by public and private entities.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] Such laws usually require entities to give clear and unambiguous notice to the individual of the types of data being collected, its reason for collection, and planned uses of the data.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] In consent-based legal frameworks, explicit consent of the individual is required as well.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] The European Union passed the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), replacing the earlier Data Protection Directive.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] The regulation was adopted on 27 April 2016.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] It became enforceable from 25 May 2018 after a two-year transition period and, unlike a directive, it does not require national governments to pass any enabling legislation, and is thus directly binding and applicable.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] "The proposed new EU data protection regime extends the scope of the EU data protection law to all foreign companies processing data of EU residents.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] In Canada, the Personal Information Protection and Electronic Documents Act (PIPEDA) regulates the collection and use of personal data and electronic documents by public and private organizations.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] PIPEDA is in effect in all federal and provincial jurisdictions, except provinces where existing privacy laws are determined to be “substantially similar”.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] Whether being regulated or self regulated, the laws require to establish ways at which access to sensitive information is limited to the people with different roles, thus in essence requiring establishment of the "sensitive data domain" model and mechanisms of its protection.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] Some of the domains have a guideline in form of pre-defined models such as "Safe Harbor" of HIPAA, based on the research of Latanya Sweeny and established privacy industry metrics.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] Additionally, many other countries have enacted their own legislature regarding data privacy protection, and more are still in the process of doing so.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] The confidentiality of sensitive business information is established through non-disclosure agreements, a legally binding contract between two parties in a professional relationship.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] NDAs may be one-way, such as in the case of an employee receiving confidential information about the employing organization, or two-way between businesses needing to share information with one another to accomplish a business goal.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] Depending on the severity of consequences, a violation of non-disclosure may result in employment loss, loss of business and client contacts, criminal charges or a civil lawsuit, and a hefty sum in damages.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] Unlike personal and private information, there is no internationally recognized framework protecting trade secrets, or even an agreed-upon definition of the term “trade secret”.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] However, many countries and political jurisdictions have taken the initiative to account for the violation of commercial confidentiality in their criminal or civil laws.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] For example, under the US Economic Espionage Act of 1996, it is a federal crime in the United States to misappropriate trade secrets with the knowledge that it will benefit a foreign power, or will injure the owner of the trade secret.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] More commonly, breach of commercial confidentiality falls under civil law, such as in the United Kingdom.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] In some developing countries, trade secret laws are either non-existent or poorly developed and offer little substantial protection.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] In many countries, unauthorized disclosure of classified information is a criminal offence, and may be punishable by fines, prison sentence, or even the death penalty, depending on the severity of the violation.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] For less severe violations, civil sanctions may be imposed, ranging from reprimand to revoking of security clearance and subsequent termination of employment.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] Whistleblowing is the intentional disclosure of sensitive information to a third-party with the intention of revealing alleged illegal, immoral, or otherwise harmful actions.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] There are many examples of present and former government employees disclosing classified information regarding national government misconduct to the public and media, in spite of the criminal consequences that await them.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] Espionage, or spying, involves obtaining sensitive information without the permission or knowledge of its holder.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] The use of spies is a part of national intelligence gathering in most countries, and has been used as a political strategy by nation-states since ancient times.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] It is unspoken knowledge in international politics that countries are spying on one another all the time, even their allies.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] Computer security is information security applied to computing and network technology, and is a significant and ever-growing field in computer science.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] The term computer insecurity, on the other hand, is the concept that computer systems are inherently vulnerable to attack, and therefore an evolving arms race between those who exploit existing vulnerabilities in security systems and those who must then engineer new mechanisms of security.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] A number of security concerns have arisen in the recent years as increasing amounts of sensitive information at every level have found their primary existence in digital form.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] At the personal level, credit card fraud, internet fraud, and other forms of identity theft have become widespread concerns that individuals need to be aware of on a day-to-day basis.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] The existence of large databases of classified information on computer networks is also changing the face of domestic and international politics.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] Cyber-warfare and cyber espionage is becoming of increasing importance to the national security and strategy of nations around the world, and it is estimated that 120 nations around the world are currently actively engaged in developing and deploying technology for these purposes.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] Philosophies and internet cultures such as open-source governance, hacktivism, and the popular hacktivist slogan "information wants to be free" reflects some of the cultural shifts in perception towards political and government secrecy.
[src:data-loss-prevention/information-sensitivity] The popular, controversial WikiLeaks is just one of many manifestations of a growing cultural sentiment that is becoming an additional challenge to the security and integrity of classified information.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] The abbreviation PII is widely used in the United States, but the phrase it abbreviates has four common variants based on *personal* or *personally*, and *identifiable* or *identifying*.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] Not all are equivalent, and for legal purposes the effective definitions vary depending on the jurisdiction and the purposes for which the term is being used.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] Under European Union and United Kingdom data protection regimes, which centre primarily on the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), the term "personal data" is significantly broader, and determines the scope of the regulatory regime.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] Personal data is defined under the GDPR as "any information which [is] related to an identified or identifiable natural person".
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] The IP address of an Internet subscriber may be classed as personal data.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] The concept of PII has become prevalent as information technology and the Internet have made it easier to collect PII leading to a profitable market in collecting and reselling PII.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] PII can also be exploited by criminals to stalk or steal the identity of a person, or to aid in the planning of criminal acts.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] As a response to these threats, many website privacy policies specifically address the gathering of PII, and lawmakers such as the European Parliament have enacted a series of legislative acts such as the GDPR to limit the distribution and accessibility of PII.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] Serious confusion arises around whether PII means information which is identifiable (that is, can be associated with a person) or identifying (that is, associated uniquely with a person, such that the PII *identifies* them).
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] In prescriptive data privacy regimes such as the US federal Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA), PII items have been specifically defined.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] In broader data protection regimes such as the GDPR, personal data is defined in a non-prescriptive principles-based way.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] Information that might not count as PII under HIPAA can be personal data for the purposes of GDPR.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] For this reason, "PII" is typically deprecated internationally.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] In the EU rules, there has been a more specific notion that the data subject can potentially be identified through additional processing of other attributes—quasi- or pseudo-identifiers.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] A simple example of this distinction: the color name "red" by itself is *not* personal data, but that same value stored as part of a person's record as their "favorite color" *is* personal data; it is the connection to the person that makes it personal data, not (as in PII) the value itself.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] The concept of information combination given in the SB1386 definition is key to correctly distinguishing PII, as defined by OMB, from "personal information", as defined by SB1386.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] Information, such as a name, that lacks context cannot be said to be SB1386 "personal information", but it must be said to be PII as defined by OMB.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] For example, the name "John Smith" has no meaning in the current context and is therefore not SB1386 "personal information", but it is PII.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] A Social Security Number (SSN) without a name or some other associated identity or context information is not SB1386 "personal information", but it is PII.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] For example, the SSN 078-05-1120 by itself is PII, but it is not SB1386 "personal information".
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] However the combination of a valid name with the correct SSN is SB1386 "personal information".
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] The combination of a name with a context may also be considered PII; for example, if a person's name is on a list of patients for an HIV clinic.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] However, it is not necessary for the name to be combined with a context in order for it to be PII.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] The reason for this distinction is that bits of information such as names, although they may not be sufficient by themselves to make an identification, may later be combined with other information to identify persons and expose them to harm.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] The scope of the term "sensitive personal data" varies by jurisdiction.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] In the UK, personal health data is treated as "sensitive" and in need of additional data protection measures.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] According to the OMB, in the United States it is not always the case that PII is "sensitive", and context may be taken into account in deciding whether certain PII is or is not sensitive.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] When a person wishes to remain anonymous, descriptions of them will often employ several of the above, such as "a 34-year-old white male who works at Target".
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] Information can still be *private*, in the sense that a person may not wish for it to become publicly known, without being personally identifiable.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] Moreover, sometimes multiple pieces of information, none sufficient by itself to uniquely identify an individual, may uniquely identify a person when combined; this is one reason that multiple pieces of evidence are usually presented at criminal trials.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] It has been shown that, in 1990, 87% of the population of the United States could be uniquely identified by gender, ZIP code, and full date of birth.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] In hacker and Internet slang, the practice of finding and releasing such information is called "doxing".
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] It is sometimes used to deter collaboration with law enforcement.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] On occasion, the doxing can trigger an arrest, particularly if law enforcement agencies suspect that the "doxed" individual may panic and disappear.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] It appears that this definition is significantly broader than the Californian example given above, and thus that Australian privacy law may cover a broader category of data and information than in some US law.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] The term "PII" is not used in Australian privacy law.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] European Union data protection law does not use the concept of personally identifiable information, and its scope is instead determined by the non-synonymous, wider concept of "personal data".
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] Further examples can be found on the EU privacy website.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] On 1 June 2023, the Hong Kong Office of the Privacy Commissioner for Personal Data published an investigation report on a data breach involving the unauthorised access of a credit reference database platform.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] The Report highlights the need for organizations to take adequate steps to protect personal data as the mere imposition of contractual obligations and policies is insufficient if such obligations and policies are not effective or are not enforced.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] The Report also clarifies that credit data is a form of "sensitive" personal data.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] The twelve Information Privacy Principles of the Privacy Act 1993 apply.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] New Zealand enacted the Privacy Act in 2020 to promote and protect individual privacy.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] The Federal Act on Data Protection of 19 June 1992 (in force since 1993) has set up a protection of privacy by prohibiting virtually any processing of personal data which is not expressly authorized by the data subjects.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] The protection is subject to the authority of the Federal Data Protection and Information Commissioner.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] Additionally, any person may ask in writing a company managing data files to correct or delete any personal data.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] The company must respond within thirty days.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] One of the primary focuses of the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) is to protect a patient's Protected Health Information (PHI), which is similar to PII.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] Senate proposed the Privacy Act of 2005, which attempted to strictly limit the display, purchase, or sale of PII without the person's consent.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] Similarly, the (proposed) Anti-Phishing Act of 2005 attempted to prevent the acquiring of PII through phishing.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] U.S. lawmakers have paid special attention to the social security number because it can be easily used to commit identity theft.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] The (proposed) Social Security Number Protection Act of 2005 and (proposed) Identity Theft Prevention Act of 2005 each sought to limit the distribution of an individual's social security number.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] Additional U.S.-specific personally identifiable information includes, but is not limited to, I-94 records, Medicaid ID numbers, and Internal Revenue Service (I.R.S.) documentation.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] Exclusivity of personally identifiable information affiliated with the U.S. highlights national data security concerns and the influence of personally identifiable information in U.S. federal data management systems.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] The National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) is a physical sciences laboratory, and a non-regulatory agency of the United States Department of Commerce.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] Its mission is to promote innovation and industrial competitiveness.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] The following are less often used to distinguish individual identity, because they are traits shared by many people.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] However, they are potentially PII, because they may be combined with other personal information to identify an individual.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] In forensics, particularly the identification and prosecution of criminals, personally identifiable information is critical in establishing evidence in criminal procedure.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] Personal data is a key component of online identity and can be exploited by individuals.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] For instance, data can be altered and used to create fake documents, hijack mail boxes and phone calls or harass people, as occurred in 2019 to a customer of the EE mobile phone operator in the UK.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] Another category can be referred to as financial identity theft, which usually entails bank account and credit card information being stolen, and then being used or sold.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] Personal data can also be used to create fake online identities, including fake accounts and profiles (which can be referred as identity cloning or identity fraud) for celebrities to gather data from other users more easily.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] Even individuals can be concerned, especially for personal purposes (this is more widely known as sockpuppetry).
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] The most critical information, such as one's password, date of birth, ID documents or social security number, can be used to log in to different websites (e.g. password reuse and account verification) to gather more information and access more content.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] Also, several agencies ask for discretion on subjects related to their work, for the safety of their employees.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] For this reason, the United States Department of Defense (DoD) has strict policies controlling release of personally identifiable information of DoD personnel.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] Many intelligence agencies have similar policies, sometimes to the point where employees do not disclose to their friends that they work for the agency.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] Similar identity protection concerns exist for witness protection programs, women's shelters, and victims of domestic violence and other threats.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] Personal information removal services work by identifying and requesting data brokers to delete the personal information of their clients.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] This process can be manual or fully automated, but it is nevertheless complex because it involves dealing with numerous data brokers, each with different policies and procedures for data removal.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] Companies offering personal information removal also face some issues.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] They struggle to ensure comprehensive data removal as new data brokers emerge and existing ones don’t always comply with removal requests.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] Most of them are also limited to certain regions or countries.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] During the second half of the 20th century, the digital revolution introduced "privacy economics", or the trade of personal data.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] The value of data can change over time and over different contexts.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] Disclosing data can reverse information asymmetry, though the costs of doing so can be unclear.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] In relation to companies, consumers often have "imperfect information regarding when their data is collected, with what purposes, and with what consequences".
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] In the mid-1990s, Varian retook the Chicago Boys approach and added a new externality, stating that the consumer would not always have perfect information on how their own data would be used.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] Laudon developed a model in which individuals own their data and have the ability to sell it as a product.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] He believed that such a system should not be regulated, to create a free market.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] In the 2000s, researchers worked on price discrimination (Taylor, 2004), two-sided markets (Cornière, 2011) and marketing strategies (Anderson and de Palma, 2012).
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] The theories became complex, and showed that the impact of privacy on the economy highly depended on the context.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] Sources, usually Internet-based since the 1990s, may include census and electoral roll records, social networking sites, court reports and purchase histories.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] The information from data brokers may be used in background checks used by employers and housing.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] There are varying regulations around the world limiting the collection of information on individuals; privacy laws vary.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] In the United States there is no federal regulation protection for the consumer from data brokers, although some states have begun enacting laws individually.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] In the European Union, GDPR serves to regulate data brokers' operations.
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] Some data brokers report to have large numbers of population data or "data attributes".
[src:data-loss-prevention/personal-data] Acxiom purports to have data from 2.5 billion different people.
